Communism Resurges in Russia
Moscow — Over a year ago, during a sabbatical from my teaching position at an American university, I returned to my hometown of Moscow.
My destination is not a bastion of free speech.
But here, some freedom still lingers.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny had traveled across the country in an effort to win support from politicians not under the Kremlin's control.
Protests erupted among the people.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate domestically.
Journalists and analysts do not necessarily follow the Kremlin's line.
And the Communist Party is widely seen as a legacy from history.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and his protest movement has been suppressed.
Its anti-corruption foundation was banned for "extremism," while its members are either exiled or under investigation.
Almost every day, journalists, media outlets, human rights advocates, or independent organizations were added to the list of "foreign agents" — and even worse, labeled as "unwelcome persons."
In the past year, Russia had slipped into a non-free state, though not far off, it was nonetheless severe.
For example, in 2012, legislation was enacted to designate foreign agents, aimed at undermining or discrediting institutions or individuals engaged in "political activities" and simultaneously receiving funds from abroad.
But the law's application has become increasingly arbitrary, with retweeting tweets now a reason for being labeled a foreign agent.
("Unwelcome persons" label could lead to complete banishment.)
) This year alone, 101 entities were added to the list of foreign agents, setting a record.
A total of 359 entities and individuals include 88 media-related institutions and persons.
According to the Russian government, the aforementioned "agents" must be listed because they "influence national politics."
But the core goal of journalism and propaganda is naturally to influence politics.
And that is precisely the problem: while President Vladimir Putin has positioned himself to continue controlling Russian politics in the foreseeable future, he perceives criticism as a survival threat.
Despite all this silence and persecution, it is the Communist Party—a most unlikely group—that has survived and become the Kremlin's only genuine opposition.
This was largely due to Navalny's "smart voting" strategy — encouraging people to support candidates most likely to defeat the Kremlin-backed nominees — which saw the Communists perform strongly in both last month's parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data showed that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the votes in the State Duma (parliament), while United Russia, backed by the Kremlin, secured nearly 49.8%.
But the Communists refused to acknowledge this result, insisting that the voting results were manipulated.
In fact, some experts estimate that they should have received around 30% of the votes, while United Russia should have garnered about 35%.
For many Russians, the Communists now seem more respectable than Putin.
But they are no longer the original Communists.
They not only do not deny earthly pleasures; on the contrary, party members wear fur coats, are enthusiastic about traveling abroad, drive foreign cars, and use social media.
Some are millionaires – such as the charming agricultural boss Pavel Grudinin (who was banned from last month’s election).
Despite being led by Genady Zyuganov, who is 77 years old, the party is increasingly influenced and supported by younger members.
For example, Nikolai Bondarchuk.
Nicknamed "Red Navalny," 36-year-old Nikolai Bondarchuk severely criticized the poorly designed pension reform in 2018.
Not long ago, when a regional minister suggested that Russians should be able to "eat better" on a meager monthly salary of 3,500 rubles (about $50), Bondarchuk documented his efforts to prove him wrong on his YouTube channel.
Despite being threatened with a ban on running, Bondarchuk was still allowed to participate in last month's State Duma election.
Although supported by Navalny's smart voting system, he still lost to the candidate from United Russia.
But his potential should not be overlooked: he recently proposed a slogan for a protest, accusing "the takeover by the state and government" of United Russia.
And then there is Anastasia Yudosova, who is 43 years old.
Like Bondarchuk, she inexplicably lost the previous election.
But she still enjoys – and increasingly so – a lot of popularity.
Thanks to the smart voting system, another rising star, elegant Ekaterina Engelicheva, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
Ironically, the Communist Party’s modernization reflects a yearning for the past: In 1917, Lenin’s Bolsheviks promised justice and equality, and although the state that embodied these ideals was strict, it was not without fairness and kindness.
Moreover, like the liberal Navalny, today's Communist Party represents a predictable and consistent vision under which someone's fanciful ideas do not affect everyone.
It is precisely based on such logic that all of the Kremlin's opponents are increasingly uniting: forming a unified "Russian Communist" front to challenge Putin's United Russia.
This situation is not limited to Russia.
In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš — also known as Czech Donald Trump — failed to remain prime minister, as the opposition coalition put aside their ideological differences and formed a common alliance, with its leader Petr Fiala likely to lead the new government alongside another opposition coalition.
As Fiala said, "People are fed up with populists," and they want "normal, competent, and decent politics."
The opposition in Hungary will also present a unified electoral list and run a single candidate for prime minister in next year's parliamentary elections.
Of course, the Czech Republic still maintains a democratic system, so Babiš is preparing to join the opposition forces.
Overthrowing Putin would be much more difficult, and it is not hard to predict that there will be even more comprehensive measures aimed at crushing the Communist Party.
But such actions also pose risks to the Kremlin.
Now the situation is that the president claims Russian democracy "has not disappeared," pointing to the presence of an "active opposition" as evidence, which indicates that he remains at least interested in pretending that Russia is not heading towards near-totalitarianism.
Putin said he just wants stability.
But its regime is pushing Russia towards greater instability.
If the Kremlin were to treat the Communist Party as it does the Russian liberals, repeatedly changing and enforcing rules to drive the party underground, then social explosions are more likely to occur.
And if it decides to stop suppressing them, Russian Communists—yes, Communist Party members—could become an不可忽视的力量.
